                <tr class='athing comtr' id='32612296'><td><table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind' indent='3'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="120"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks">
      <center><a id='up_32612296'href='vote?id=32612296&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D32611247'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center>    </td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=mrtksn" class="hnuser">mrtksn</a> <span class="age" title="2022-08-26T20:20:44"><a href="item?id=32612296">42 days ago</a></span> <span id="unv_32612296"></span>          <span class='navs'>
             | <a href="#32611823" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">root</a> | <a href="#32612154" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">parent</a> | <a href="#32613981" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">next</a> <a class="togg clicky" id="32612296" n="4" href="javascript:void(0)">[–]</a><span class="onstory"></span>          </span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="commtext c00">I speak 3 languages, attempted to learn the 4th one (German) on Duolingo and I find it very ineffective.<p>I recall having trouble learning English back in high school and then having a breakthrough. The breakthrough was, I figured out how to think in English when trying to debug my errors with the teacher who actually have lived in the USA. Once it clicked, I no longer had to memorise things but predict instead. My English is still not perfect but I can have fluent conversations and almost never need to look up words, I can figure out the meaning of idioms etc.<p>IMHO, the gamification in Duolingo is not geared towards making you figure out the mechanics behind the language. I think edge case exploration is way to go but the gamification usually revolves around memorising.</span>
              <div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                  </font>
      </div></div></td></tr>
