            <tr class='athing comtr' id='32612134'><td><table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind' indent='2'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="80"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks">
      <center><a id='up_32612134'href='vote?id=32612134&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D32611247'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center>    </td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=samwillis" class="hnuser">samwillis</a> <span class="age" title="2022-08-26T20:07:03"><a href="item?id=32612134">42 days ago</a></span> <span id="unv_32612134"></span>          <span class='navs'>
             | <a href="#32611951" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">root</a> | <a href="#32612056" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">parent</a> | <a href="#32612356" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">prev</a> | <a href="#32612304" class="clicky" aria-hidden="true">next</a> <a class="togg clicky" id="32612134" n="6" href="javascript:void(0)">[–]</a><span class="onstory"></span>          </span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="commtext c00">Yes, architecture and design is an art form, the medium in which you work influences the design process and the output you create. I’m not saying all architects and designers should return to the drafting table, but it is a shame that the knowledge of how to work like that is disappearing from the workplace.<p>Also, not everything always needs to be “efficient”, what’s wrong with working slowly if you can then create an even better result.</span>
