                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="commtext c00">Not sure. I know that the conglomerate Outokumpu once had a pilot plant with high-Tc superconducting magnets deployed in the Amazon region somewhere (&#x27;Ice in the jungle&#x27;? Hah, hold my beer, try liquid-helium cooled superconducting magnets in the jungle).<p>I know because a colleague joined the company, and one of his first assignments was to diagnose unexpectedly large helium losses. A quick FFT later of the recorded Dewar flask levels revealed a 24-hour periodicity, and further analysis found that for a couple of hours every day, the full heat of the tropical sun was finding its way to the tin roof of the mine shed housing the superconducting magnet systems.<p>I haven&#x27;t heard anything more about the technology or its economics&#x2F;scaling since then. But I also certainly haven&#x27;t heard anything more about its use with landfill-derived feedstocks, which seems like a reasonable move.</span>
              <div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                  </font>
